{"source_key":"sha256-ea08d35f42d5530fbe92c80d4f5b27e9","record_index":965,"record_hash":"sha256:ced3b91ddd8575fefdf7eafbe5d1a87097d566e35ad54d64dc42d2f217aa372b","timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:12:50.315Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 835914\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1152\nOutput:\n## Filesystem / Cache Architecture\n\nThe generator needs a real local filesystem. Treat the Git/GitMeta cache as a\nlocal working set, not as durable product data.\n\nRecommended v1 architecture:\n\n```text\nweb/API facade -> generator HTTP API -> one generator process\n                                  -> one mounted persistent volume\n```\n\nUse object storage only for backups, exported projection JSON, or archived\nsnapshots. Do not try to run the live Git object database or GitMeta SQLite\nstate directly on S3/R2/Tigris-style object storage.\n\nWhy:\n\n- Git repositories expect filesystem behavior: directories, many small files,\n  atomic renames, file locks, and random reads.\n- `git-meta-lib` currently materializes state into `.git/git-meta.sqlite` next\n  to the repository. That also wants a normal local filesystem.\n- SQLite's WAL documentation says all processes using a database must be on the\n  same host and WAL does not work over a network filesystem\n  ([SQLite WAL](https://www.sqlite.org/wal.html)). Avoid clever shared-network\n  filesystem designs unless there is a strong reason.\n\nLightweight hosting options that fit:\n\n- Fly.io Machine + Fly Volume. Fly volumes are local persistent storage for Fly\n  Machines and get daily snapshots\n  ([Fly volumes](https://fly.io/docs/volumes/overview/)).\n- Render background worker or private service + persistent disk. Render supports\n  disks for paid services and background workers\n  ([Render disks](https://render.com/docs/disks)).\n- Railway service + volume. Railway volumes mount persistent read/write storage\n  into a service\n  ([Railway volumes](https://docs.railway.com/volumes)).\n\nAWS can solve this, but it is heavier than needed for v1. Lambda/ECS can mount\nEFS ([Lambda EFS](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html),\n[ECS EFS](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html)),\nbut that introduces VPC, mount targ\n[TRUNCATED]\nse numeric GitHub repository ids or opaque hashes for filesystem paths. Keep\nowner/repo names as display metadata, not path authority.\n\nConcurrency model:\n\n- Start with one generator process attached to one volume.\n- Use a per-repository lock around repo initialization, fetch, GitMeta\n  materialization, and projection.\n- Do not let multiple generator instances write the same repository cache.\n- If more capacity is needed, shard repositories across workers by GitHub repo\n  id, or put generation jobs in a queue and route each repo to one owner worker.\n- The web/API facade should not mount or inspect the repository volume.\n\nCache policy:\n\n- The repository cache is rebuildable from public metadata refs, so it is not\n  critical durable data.\n- Generated projections can be regenerated as long as the metadata ref still\n  exists. Store them for speed and stable user experience, not as the only copy\n  of evidence.\n- Keep quotas from day one: max repos, max bytes per repo, total volume high\n  watermark, LRU eviction, negative-cache TTL for missing metadata, and\n  per-repo fetch debounce.\n- Deleting a repository cache must happen under that repo's lock.\n\nBackup policy:\n\n- For v1, rely on provider volume snapshots plus the fact that repo caches are\n  rebuildable.\n- If generator-local SQLite becomes important, add a real SQLite backup path\n  rather than copying live database files. Litestream can replicate SQLite to\n  S3-compatible storage ([Litestream](https://litestream.io/getting-started/)).\n- Do not back up huge live Git caches unless there is measured evidence that\n  warm-cache loss is painful.\n\nThis keeps the first production setup small: one container, one volume, one\nservice API, and a rebuildable cache. The escape hatch is straightforward: add\nobject storage for projection exports or backups, then shard generator workers\nonly when load proves it is needed.\n\n## Online Research Findings (2026-05-24)\n\nResearch was split across three lanes: Pierre/code.storage, deployment/runtime\nfit, and Rust-to-Node integration.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:12:50.315Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}